        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="Printed letterhead."/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><persName>D. J. WORKUM</persName>,</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">MANUFACTURER AND JOBBER OF</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">HATS, CAPS &amp; GENTS' FURNISHING GOODS,</p>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>NO. 42 WOODWARD AVENUE</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">____________</p>
            <p><placeName>Detroit</placeName>, <date>Febr 14 1867</date></p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Phild</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">My Dear friend</p>
            <p>I rejoice to learn of your safe return &amp; I<lb/> trust with <sic>renewd</sic>
                rigour &amp; strength I have<lb/> just read this months Occident—disappointed—I<lb/>
                fully anticipated to read your full account of places<lb/> visited their synagogues.<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Prepress</hi> numbers &amp;c<lb/> It would prove interesting to
                your readers,<lb/> None regretted the sudden loss of that Pious good<lb/> woman
                    <persName>Mrs. Osterman</persName> (Peace on her Soul) than<lb/> myself &amp;
                would more rejoice at her not forgetting<lb/> the worthy in her will. I cannot but
                congratulate<lb/> you &amp; I doubt not you will find it useful<lb/> for I presume
                your Income not as great as<lb/> to enable you to keep a large Bank account<lb/> to
                your Credit. I have now resided here<lb/> nearly Two Years without joining either
                Congregation<lb/> The Polish Minhag I do not so much object<lb/> to as the mixing
                with its worshipers. You may blame</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>me but were you here in my situation you would<lb/> act the same. My immediate
                kindest &amp; best Friends<lb/> (Friends not only in words but noble actions) are
                there<lb/> Connected with the Reform Synagogue my <add>?</add> &amp;<lb/> visitors
                are the same while the others I know not<lb/> &amp; from what I see of them care not
                to know<lb/> I have at times visited their Synagogue &amp; the service<lb/> is not
                what I admire. Give me the <sic>Pourtugese</sic><lb/> service above all others for
                solemnity. The<lb/> Minister of the <placeName>Revard St</placeName> Synagogue
                    <persName>Mr Epstine</persName><lb/> is a very talented man He Preaches every
                    <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> alternately English, German his Synagogue is well<lb/>
                attended. He has that happy oratory of mastering his<lb/> hearers feel his words
                &amp; frequently the whole audience<lb/> are in tears at the strength of his
                Inspiring words<lb/> The Polish Synagogue is fairly attended they have a Hazan<lb/>
                but no Preacher, <persName>Mrs Hart</persName> &amp; family write<lb/> with myself
                in kind regards</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">With your friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Hart</persName>
            </p>
            <p>We have formed a <add>social</add> Club of about 45 Members,<lb/> Cards, Dramatic
                Performances, Lectures, Concerts Balls<lb/> &amp;c. Two Performances in English
                &amp; one in German<lb/> by the Members <add>their</add> wives &amp; Sisters was
                played equal to any stage</p>
